EXT. DAWES FARMHOUSE - NIGHT

Cricket loads something heavy, tarped, into the truck bed. Peg stands on the porch, arms crossed against the chill.

PEG:
You could just be an old man whose barn got robbed by his own government. That's plenty. Nobody'd think less of you for stopping there.

CRICKET:
I know it.

He gets in the truck. She doesn't ask him to stay. She doesn't wave either. Just watches the taillights out to the road.

EXT. FEDERAL COMPLIANCE FIELD OFFICE - NIGHT

The gravel lot behind the storefront, empty, chain-link, the HARMONY IS A VERB poster lit faint through the glass.

Cricket's truck idles at the lot's edge, lights off. He sets a mortar tube in a coffee can of sand, unhurried, the way he'd run any checklist. Touches a punk stick to a road flare until it catches.

CRICKET:
(quiet, to no one)
Fire in the hole.

The first shell goes up with a crack that lights the whole lot red, then green, then a shower of gold that hangs a long time over the flat highway dark.

One old man stands in the falling light, face turned up, not moving.

A second shell. A third.

On the fourth, headlights swing into the lot. The car eases to a stop. WADE gets out, hand nowhere near his holster, and looks at the sky a second before he looks at Cricket.

WADE:
(finally)
That a Class C or a Class B mortar, Earl?

CRICKET:
C. I'm not an idiot, Wade.

WADE:
(getting out his citation book, slow)
No sir. Turn around for me.

INT. COUNTY COURTHOUSE, COURTROOM - DAY

A small county courtroom, half empty. Cricket alone at the defense table in his one good jacket. Peg sits in the front row, spine straight, hands folded like church. A YOUNG PROSECUTOR shuffles papers. JUDGE ORVAL BENNING, 70s, black robe, reading glasses low on his nose.

CLERK:
(reading)
Unlawful discharge of consumer fireworks. Trespass on federal leasehold.

JUDGE BENNING:
(not looking up)
How does the defendant plead?

CRICKET:
Guilty, Your Honor.

JUDGE BENNING:
(to the prosecutor)
Anybody hurt?

PROSECUTOR:
No, Your Honor.

JUDGE BENNING:
Property damage?

PROSECUTOR:
A scorched patch of gravel, Your Honor.

JUDGE BENNING:
(a long look at Cricket over his glasses)
I was nine years old in my daddy's living room the night men from this state walked on the Moon. Watched it on a television the size of a bread box.
(beat)
Time served. Four hundred dollars, plus the cost of the gravel. I've got real criminals on this morning's docket, Mr. Dawes. Get on home.

He bangs the gavel before the prosecutor can get a word in.

EXT. COUNTY COURTHOUSE - DAY

Cricket comes down the steps into the sun. Peg's already at the truck, door open, waiting.

PEG:
Well?

CRICKET:
Four hundred dollars and a lecture from a nine-year-old.

PEG:
(the ghost of a smile)
Get in. Supper's cold.

They drive off. The courthouse flag hangs still in the windless morning.

CUT TO:
